node.text:
Just like consumer cars have to undergo crash testing, so do commercial semitrucks. While some of these tests are the same that production cars undergo, others are designed specifically for trucks. 

Thanks to trucking companies like Volvo and Scania as well as the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, safety standards for these trucks are only improving.

node.text: Vietnamese woodworker Truong Van Dao built a fully drivable wooden Bugatti. It’s one third the size of an actual car, but a near replica of the luxury automaker’s $8.9 million Centodieci hypercar. We explore how he did the entire project in just 40 days.

node.title: How to build a fully drivable wooden Bugatti

node.text: A wave of upcoming hypercars claim to accelerate 0 to 60 mph in as little as 1.7 seconds. However, nothing has been verified. The reality is that no production car has ever managed an official 0 to 60 time of under 2 seconds. There's a reason for that. We break down how current technology has created that limit, and what could be done to break it.

node.title: Why going 0 to 60 mph in under 2 seconds is almost impossible

node.text: The Maruti Suzuki S-Presso, a crossover SUV sold in India, recently made headlines when it received a zero-star crash-test rating. We explore what it takes to completely fail a crash test and what could make a modern car so unsafe.

#tesla #truck #engineering

node.text:
Larry Kosilla is a professional car detailing and owner of AMMO NYC, a car cleaning supply and detailing company. He demonstrates the techniques he uses to clean a car that has been neglected and sitting outside for years. The SUV has significant moisture, rodent, and mold problems. Cleaning this car will include cleaning out rain rails, sucking out rat excrement from the carpet, and repairing the foggy headlights. 

#suv #cleaning #cars #deepclean

node.title: How Cars Are Professionally Detailed and Deep Cleaned

In 2019, the Bugatti Chiron Super Sport 300  became the first production car to drive 300 mph. This was almost 15 years after the Bugatti Veyron became the first to reach 250. So why did it take so long for automakers to build a car just 50 mph faster? We explore what makes 300 mph such a difficult benchmark to reach and what automakers like Bugatti have been doing to chase it.

#cars #speed #bugatti #sportscar

node.title: Why It's Almost Impossible For Cars To Go 300 Miles Per Hour

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shows AT&T's Flying COW drone in the air. It is overlaid with the article headline that reads: "Take a look at At&T's 'Flying COWs' — drones that returned cell service to Hurricane Ida-hit Louisiana." There is an arrow indicating the ability to swipe through the post.

node.text:
AT&T's Flying COW, which stands for Cell-on-Wings, is a new technology aimed at providing wireless coverage during natural disasters and big events.

This week, Hurricane Ida devastated much of the southeast, and AT&T's Flying COW was able to help keep friends and family in contact amid the power outages.

The device is a cell site situated on a drone engineered to beam wireless LTE coverage across an area of up to 40 square miles.

The weather-resistant device can withstand extreme conditions, and its thermal imaging can help search and rescue teams find people in buildings, tree cover, and thick smoke.

Read more about AT&T's Flying COW at the link in our bio.
 
Story by Taylor Rains.

(Credit: AT&T)

It is engineered to beam widespread satellite coverage to crowds of people during natural disasters and large events."

node.text:
On Tuesday, Apple's CEO Tim Cook released a statement announcing that the tech company would invest more money into their Racial Equity and Justice Initiative. The $30 million investment comes after Apple initially invested $100 million to start the fund in January.

The new funds will focus primarily on advancing education and career-development opportunities for Hispanic people. There are three sections of the investment: education, entrepreneurship, and criminal-justice reform. 

Apple is one of many large corporations that have set up funds focusing on diversity over the past year. 

Read more of Marguerite Ward's story at the link in our bio.

node.text:

Tech reviewer Marques Brownlee went through his issues with the yoke in a recent video.

Click the link in our bio to see his full review.

(Credit: Tesla)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of Tesla's rectangle steering yoke with the headline, "One of the world's most popular tech reviewers highlighted the downsides of Tesla's new steering yoke."

Text graphic with the text, "Tesla caused a stir in January when it announced that it was changing the wheel in its Model S sedans and Model X SUVs. The rectangular steerer is one of the more controversial features Tesla has released lately. Tech reviewer Marques Brownlee went through his issues with the new feature in a recent video. "

Text graphic with the text, "According to Brownlee, the yoke seems impractical for driving. Your hands can really only be in one position, making it hard to turn the wheel around to park, for example. Tesla moved lots of essential functions — like turn signals, headlights, and windshield wipers — to touch-sensitive buttons on the steering yoke itself. Even after hundreds of miles of driving, Brownlee found he would still accidentally press the buttons when turning."

Text graphic with the text, "Brownlee also criticized Tesla's decision to make the horn a button on the yoke, rather than put it in the center like on every other car. He pointed out that people have developed muscle memory over years of driving to slam the horn when something dangerous is about to happen, and said turning the horn into a little touch-sensitive button makes that needlessly complicated."
Photo by Tech Insider on August 30, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'INSIDER Apple may have snuck a peek at a new, notchless iPhone in the latest episode of 'Ted Lasso''.

node.text:
Apple TV's hit show "Ted Lasso" may have had its most high-profile cameo yet, the upcoming iPhone 13.

The phone appears to lack a front-screen notch. The iPhone 13 is expected to have one, but much smaller.

The device could have merely been a prop in the show, engineered to appear as a notchless iPhone. But Apple fans and critics have long bemoaned the smartphone notch.

Amazon is entering the delayed pay arena after announcing its partnership with "buy now, pay later" platform provider Affirm on Friday.

The e-commerce giant's "pay-over-time" option will be available at checkout, allowing Amazon consumers to split the cost of purchases of $50 or more into smaller monthly installments dispersed over a longer period of time.

The payment option is only available to a select few right now, but Amazon plans to release it broadly to all consumers in the coming months.

The organizers of a campaign calling on past and present Apple employees to share their accounts of workplace bullying, harassment, and discrimination say they have received hundreds of responses from the company's retail staff, with many claiming they faced hostility in the workplace.

The outpouring of complaints from Apple's in-store employees comes amid a wave of activism among tech company's non-corporate employees as those on the lower rungs of Big Tech's labor force push for change.
